{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"51062a92-2472-49ae-ae9f-51df4c9ead73","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**To copy the trace off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container image, you can alternatively use **PerfView** or **dotnet-monitor** as a sidecar. For production, `dotnet-monitor` is preferred — it exposes an HTTP endpoint to trigger trace collection without exec'ing into the container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f7ff5e77-9b4c-47b6-9435-2d09f82e9e64","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":358},"id":"11dd3855-947e-48c4-a230-c5a860a7be39","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:47:36.020Z","parentId":"536007e3-ae96-4b2f-9128-d3d3070fad09"}
